@*
    IMPORTANT NOTE:
    ***************
    This "Delete" view is intentionally kept for LEARNING and DEMONSTRATION purposes only.

    In this project, we are using a more streamlined and modern approach:
        - Deleting items directly from the list page (Instruments.cshtml)
        - Using a <form method="post"> with a Delete button
        - Adding a JavaScript confirmation dialog (confirm())
        (Please review the code in the instruments.cshtml)

    Therefore:
        - This Delete.cshtml view is NOT used in the current application flow
        - No [HttpGet] Delete action exists to load this view

    WHEN WOULD THIS VIEW BE USED?
    *****************************
    In a more traditional or enterprise-level MVC pattern, Delete is implemented in TWO steps:

    1) GET => Load confirmation page that has the full form's fields filled with the current item info
       Example: GET /Instruments/Delete/7

        Controller:
            [HttpGet]
            public IActionResult Delete(int? id)

        This view (Delete.cshtml) would display:
            - Instrument details
            - "Are you sure?" confirmation message

    2) POST => Perform the actual deletion
        Example: POST /Instruments/Delete/7

        Controller:
            [HttpPost]
            [ValidateAntiForgeryToken]
                public IActionResult Delete(int? id)

    WHY WE DID NOT USE THIS APPROACH:
    ********************************
    - It requires:
        - An extra controller action (GET)
        - An extra view (which is this file "Delete.cshtml")
    - Adds more complexity for a simple operation

    Instead, we used the following approach:
        - Direct POST from the list page
        - JavaScript confirm() for user confirmation
        - Cleaner and faster user experience

    SUMMARY:
    ********
    - This view is NOT used in the current implementation
    - It is kept only to demonstrate the "confirmation page" pattern approach
    - In real projects, BOTH approaches are valid depending on requirements

    Link: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/mvc/controllers/actions
    Link: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/security/anti-request-forgery
*@

<form asp-action="Delete" method="post">
    @Html.AntiForgeryToken()
    @* Example placeholder: in real usage, we would pass the Id here *@
    @* <input type="hidden" name="id" value="@Model.Id" /> *@

    <button type="submit">Delete</button>
</form>